ormation about the river into a non-technical overview of its ecology. Strayer describes the geography and geology of the Hudson and its basin, the properties of water and its movements in the river, water chemistry, and the river’s plants and animals. He then takes a more detailed look at the Hudson’s ecosystems and each of its major habitats. Strayer also discusses important management challenges facing the river today, including pollution, habitat destruction, overfishing, invasive species, and ecological restoration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnvironmental protectionxHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aEnvironmental protectionzHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aEstuarine healthxHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aEstuarine healthzHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aHuman ecologyxHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aHuman ecologyzHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aNatural historyxHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aNatural historyzHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aNaturexEffect of human beings onxHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aNaturexEffect of human beings onzHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aRestoration ecologyxHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aRestoration ecologyzHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aStream ecologyxHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aStream ecologyzHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aWaterxPollutionxHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aWaterxPollutionzHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 7aNATURE / Ecology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095239340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520952393423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520952393/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  